A convenient way to attack this problem (and avoid the ambiguities of ASCII‐art diagrams) is to place the spiral on a standard “axial‐coordinate” system for a hexagonal lattice and then work out which six cells neighbor 2026.  One may do this as follows.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1)  Identify which “ring” 2026 lies on.
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

In a regular hex‐spiral numbering,  
 •  The center (ring 0) is just 1.  
 •  Ring n (n ≥ 1) contains 6n numbers, running from  
       L(n−1)+1   up to   L(n)   where  
       L(n) = 1 + 3n(n+1).  
Thus ring 1 has the 6 numbers 2–7, ring 2 has the 12 numbers 8–19, ring 3 has 18 numbers 20–37, etc.

We want n so that  
    L(n−1) < 2026  ≤  L(n).

A quick check shows

   L(25) = 1 + 3·25·26 = 1951,     L(26) = 1 + 3·26·27 = 2107.

Since 1951 < 2026 ≤ 2107, the number 2026 sits on ring 26.  That ring has 6×26 = 156 numbers, namely 1952 through 2107.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2)  Set up axial coordinates and locate 2026.
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

A common axial‐coordinate convention for a hex grid is to let each cell be labeled (q,r), with the “hex distance” from (0,0) given by

   dist(q,r) = ( |q| + |r| + |q + r| ) / 2.

•  The center 1 is at (0,0).  
•  Ring n is all cells whose distance from (0,0) is exactly n.  
•  One can enumerate ring n by starting at the “corner”  (n,0)  and moving counterclockwise in six straight segments of length n.

In fact, for ring n the first label on that ring is

   S(n) = L(n−1) + 1 = 3n(n−1) + 2,

so for n = 26 one gets

   S(26) = 3·26·25 + 2 = 1952.

Hence the 156 cells of ring 26 are labeled 1952, 1953, …, 2107 as one goes around.

We want the index k for which 1952 + k = 2026, i.e. k = 74 (counting from 0).  One then breaks the ring into six segments (each of length 26).  Let

   k = 0..155,   segment  s = ⌊k/26⌋,   offset  t = k mod 26.

Here, k = 74 implies  
   s =  ⌊74/26⌋ = 2,    t = 74 − 2·26 = 22.

Each segment s corresponds to one of the six “straight” directions around the ring.  In particular, the corner coordinates for ring 26 are

   corner₀ = (26, 0),
   corner₁ = corner₀ + 26·(−1, +1) = (0, 26),
   corner₂ = corner₁ + 26·(−1,  0) = (−26, 26),
   … etc.

Since s = 2,  we start at  corner₂ = (−26, 26)  and move in direction d₂ = (0, −1).  An offset of t = 22  means

   (q, r) = corner₂ + 22·(0, −1) = (−26, 26 − 22) = (−26, 4).

Hence in axial coordinates, 2026 sits at (−26, 4).

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3)  Find its six neighbors.
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The six “axial” steps from any cell (q,r) are:

   (−1,+1),   (−1, 0),   ( 0,−1),   (+1,−1),   (+1, 0),   ( 0,+1).

Applying these to (−26, 4) gives:

   N₀ = (−27,  5),
   N₁ = (−27,  4),
   N₂ = (−26,  3),
   N₃ = (−25,  3),
   N₄ = (−25,  4),
   N₅ = (−26,  5).

Next one computes each neighbor’s distance from (0,0) to see which ring it lies on:

 •  N₀ = (−27, 5).  
      q+r = −22;  |−27|+|5|+|−22|=27+5+22=54 → dist=54/2=27 → ring 27.  
 •  N₁ = (−27, 4).  
      q+r = −23;  sum=27+4+23=54 → dist=27 → ring 27.  
 •  N₂ = (−26, 3).  
      q+r = −23;  sum=26+3+23=52 → dist=26 → ring 26.  
 •  N₃ = (−25, 3).  
      q+r = −22;  sum=25+3+22=50 → dist=25 → ring 25.  
 •  N₄ = (−25, 4).  
      q+r = −21;  sum=25+4+21=50 → dist=25 → ring 25.  
 •  N₅ = (−26, 5).  
      q+r = −21;  sum=26+5+21=52 → dist=26 → ring 26.

Thus two neighbors fall in ring 25, two in ring 26, two in ring 27.  One can find each neighbor’s label by the same “segment‐and‐offset” method used above.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
(a)  The two neighbors in ring 26
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Ring 26 starts at label 1952.  
We already know how to convert a coordinate to its k  (0–155).  

 •  (−26, 3).  From corner₂ = (−26, 26), moving direction (0,−1),  
      we need  26 − t = 3 → t = 23  steps,  
      so k = 2×26 + 23 = 75.  
      Label = 1952 + 75 = 2027.

 •  (−26, 5).  Similarly  26 − t = 5 → t = 21,  
      so k = 2×26 + 21 = 73.  
      Label = 1952 + 73 = 2025.

So the ring‐26 neighbors are 2025 and 2027.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
(b)  The two neighbors in ring 25
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Ring 25 runs from  
   S(25) = 3·25² −3·25 +2 = 1802  
up to  1951.

 •  N₃ = (−25, 3).  Corner₂ for ring 25 is (−25, 25).  
    Moving (0,−1), we want  25 − t = 3 → t=22 → k=2×25+22=72.  
    Label = 1802 +72 = 1874.

 •  N₄ = (−25, 4).  Likewise  25 − t =4 → t=21 → k=71.  
    Label = 1802 +71 = 1873.

So the ring‐25 neighbors are 1873 and 1874.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
(c)  The two neighbors in ring 27
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Ring 27 goes from  
   S(27) = 3·27² −3·27 +2 = 2108  
up to  2108 + 6·27 −1 = 2269.

 •  N₀ = (−27, 5)  lies on the segment from corner₂ = (−27, 27)  
    moving (0,−1).  One needs  27−t=5 → t=22 → k=2×27+22=76.  
    Label = 2108 +76 = 2184.

 •  N₁ = (−27, 4).  Then  27−t=4 → t=23 → k=77.  
    Label = 2108 +77 = 2185.

So the ring‐27 neighbors are 2184 and 2185.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
4)  Add them all up.
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Hence the six neighbors of 2026 are  
  2025, 2027, 1873, 1874, 2184, 2185.

Their sum is

  2025 + 2027 + 1873 + 1874 + 2184 + 2185  
  = (2025 +2027) + (1873 +1874) + (2184 +2185)  
  = 4052 + 3747 + 4369  
  = 12168.

Answer:  12168.
